Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! Welcome to our 4th Weekly Dose of Optimism, where we celebrat=
e the incredible accomplishments humans manage to pull off and the progress=
 that we=E2=80=99re =E2=80=94 unsteadily and windingly =E2=80=94 making.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
(1) Brain-Computer Interface Startup Implants First Device in US Patient [h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/207508b2-0c26-4e21-9003-9e88debbe574?u=3D16283=
549]
Ashlee Vance [https://substack.com/redirect/f6f5a74b-f1a7-4904-9198-78afd18=
ec4a7?u=3D16283549] for Bloomberg
I feel like we are at the beginning of a renaissance around brain decoding.
In early July, a startup called Synchron [https://substack.com/redirect/104=
378f9-4232-48cb-b90f-11e378780507?u=3D16283549] implanted a device into the=
 brain of a patient with ALS that will let the patient use the internet, te=
xt, and email, just by thinking. This is sci-fi happening in real-time, and=
 benefiting people afflicted with crippling diseases first. Synchron has al=
ready implanted devices in Australian patients, and there=E2=80=99s a long =
way to go before we live in the world Tim Urban described in Neuralink and =
the Brain=E2=80=99s Magical Future [https://substack.com/redirect/1698c35d-=
ba40-4207-b320-1d51425451a8?u=3D16283549], but it=E2=80=99s an incredible s=
tep.
(2) Two Companies Aim to Beat SpaceX to Mars With =E2=80=98Audacious=E2=80=
=99 Landing [https://substack.com/redirect/3ec7e458-09f9-475b-92fe-bf1f4203=
ff34?u=3D16283549]
Kenneth Chang for The New York Times
Timothy Ellis, the chief executive and a founder of Relativity, said the wa=
y that SpaceX aspired to do things =E2=80=9Cat the edge of crazy and ambiti=
ous and audacious=E2=80=9D was an inspiration.
=E2=80=9CThose kinds of goals attract the best people to work on them,=E2=
=80=9D Mr. Ellis said. =E2=80=9CWe are more audacious than some of the othe=
r companies.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CI feel like if it=E2=80=99s not something that=E2=80=99s challengi=
ng and that people think is difficult and you may not be able to do it, it=
=E2=80=99s not hard enough,=E2=80=9D [Impulse Space Founder] Mr. [Thomas] M=
ueller said. =E2=80=9CWe need to do stuff that people think can=E2=80=99t b=
e done.=E2=80=9D
Two startups, Relativity Space and Impulse Space, announce that they=E2=80=
=99ve teamed up to attempt the first private space mission to Mars, which t=
hey hope to launch as soon as two and a half years from now, when Earth and=
 Mars line up next. An announcement =E2=89=A0 a successful mission, and a l=
ot needs to go right for the two companies to pull it off, but I love the a=
udacity of the plan.=20
Free version of the announcement at businesswire [https://substack.com/redi=
rect/ca452fbd-9700-4477-8633-6e5b4cc8b13f?u=3D16283549]
(3) How We Will Fight Climate Change [https://substack.com/redirect/7668838=
5-43a5-4121-b9ff-e24d2aa5bea0?u=3D16283549]
Noah Smith
It is now time to conclude that the =E2=80=9Cscare people into making a big=
 push=E2=80=9D strategy that climate activists and leftists have been using=
 over the last few years has decisively, utterly failed. People ought to be=
 scared. They ought to support a big push. But this is simply a thing that =
is not going to happen in the time frame we need it to happen.
I enjoy Noah Smith=E2=80=99s writing because he=E2=80=99s a pragmatic optim=
ist who proposes realistic solutions to the problems at hand. In this piece=
, he rails against the degrowth, anti-capitalism, and doomerism of much of =
the environmental movement before proposing a path forward: =E2=80=9CA tech=
nology-focused, bottom-up, whole-of-society effort.=E2=80=9D Fighting clima=
te change, and creating abundant energy, will require both capitalist effor=
ts and government subsidies, national, state, and local action, and individ=
ual efforts, coming together in what Robinson Meyer calls a =E2=80=9Cgreen =
vortex [https://substack.com/redirect/3d3025e1-e0dd-4af1-8afa-42aa8acca486?=
u=3D16283549]=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9Chow policy, technology, business, and poli=
tics can all work together, lowering the cost of zero-carbon energy, buildi=
ng pro-climate coalitions, and speeding up humanity=E2=80=99s ability to de=
carbonize.=E2=80=9D
Smith=E2=80=99s climate plan is a piece of what Derek Thompson calls the Ab=
undance Agenda [https://substack.com/redirect/1c3ee2cf-5078-4924-9e50-f582a=
2c76103?u=3D16283549]: a non-partisan push to create more of all of the thi=
ngs that we need, including housing, healthcare, and of course, energy. Wha=
t I love about both Smith and Thompson=E2=80=99s approaches is that they fo=
cus on benefits instead of fear.=20
Pair with: What Joe Manchin Cost Us [https://substack.com/redirect/41206dc2=
-4495-44f5-b231-4dfd32235288?u=3D16283549] by Leah C. Stokes in The New Yor=
k Times=20
(4) What I Miss About Working at Stripe [https://substack.com/redirect/b15d=
e97a-40d5-460c-affe-7375786ed10c?u=3D16283549]
Brie Wolfson in Every
It=E2=80=99s more about missing that universal agreement that it=E2=80=99s =
really, really cool to devote yourself fully to your work. And to expect th=
at from your colleagues in a way that makes you feel that =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=
=99re all really, really, really in this together=E2=80=9D kind of way.
Over the weekend, I started writing a piece, inspired by The Bear [https://=
substack.com/redirect/33a5a0e8-56a8-4e7b-adea-9ba5e46024a1?u=3D16283549], a=
bout the importance of working really hard and giving a shit about the qual=
ity of your work.=20
Simply put: achieving great things =E2=80=94 like building Stripe, running =
a world-class restaurant, or pulling off anything that we=E2=80=99ve linked=
 to in Weekly Dose of Optimism =E2=80=94 requires passion bordering on obse=
ssion and a boatload of hours.=20
Wolfson=E2=80=99s piece is a celebration of the magic that comes from being=
 a part of a team that=E2=80=99s working incredibly hard together and a goo=
d reminder that great progress requires great effort.
(5) A Weird, Wonderful Conversation With Kim Stanley Robinson [https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/8e8b6d12-7990-4f82-8e17-6f6ce874fdac?u=3D16283549] (=F0=
=9F=8E=A7)
The Ezra Klein Show [https://substack.com/redirect/697de6e6-2a76-419d-88c2-=
d828e0824ed1?u=3D16283549]
In our culture, to say you=E2=80=99re optimistic is maybe not the right thi=
ng, but hope, optimism=E2=80=A6 this attitude is a necessary political stan=
ce to take because we are in a position of privilege and the situation can =
be saved and given those two, it=E2=80=99s dereliction of duty to be pessim=
istic, to be cynical. It=E2=80=99s just a chicken thing to do.=20
We need to be strong in a moment of crisis by saying, yes, it can be done. =
And if we=E2=80=99re in a race between bad catastrophe and some kind of beg=
inning prosperity for all =E2=80=94 when you=E2=80=99re in a race that inte=
nse, you don=E2=80=99t want to sit down on the ground and start crying. Oh,=
 we=E2=80=99ve lost already. That would be a bad thing to do, because you=
=E2=80=99re in a race.
You actually need to run as hard as you can. If you lose the race, well, th=
at is a dystopian novel. And I don=E2=80=99t really want to go there. If we=
 lose the race, we=E2=80=99re in terrible trouble, and we=E2=80=99ll be in =
emergency mode for years. But if we win the race, it=E2=80=99s a big win fo=
r the biosphere, for the other creatures, for humanity. So it=E2=80=99s wor=
th pretending to be optimistic, or using optimism as a club, and beating it=
 with people. Yes, we can succeed. Bang, bang, bang.
Kim Stanley Robinson is the author of The Mars Trilogy and The Ministry for=
 the Future, and is quickly becoming one of my favorites. His near-future s=
ci-fi paints imaginable worlds. His conversation with Ezra Klein is delight=
ful, and while I don=E2=80=99t agree with him on everything, few people hav=
e used writing to help create a better future as beautifully as KSR has. A =
great podcast for a little weekend walk outside.=20
Bonus: Roots of Progress is Looking for a CEO [https://substack.com/redirec=
t/307d45d0-f5d4-454e-8a00-adf663f38790?u=3D16283549]
Jason Crawford=E2=80=99s Roots of Progress is one of the progress studies m=
ovement=E2=80=99s home bases. Its mission is to =E2=80=9Cestablish a new ph=
ilosophy of progress [https://substack.com/redirect/540b2c9f-6b90-4ba3-b661=
-fbba1756a532?u=3D16283549] for the 21st century and beyond=E2=80=94one bas=
ed on the ideas of humanism and agency [https://substack.com/redirect/f357d=
24c-02a4-405f-a348-dde94d3ef2e5?u=3D16283549], and one that puts forth a bo=
ld, ambitious vision for the technological future.=E2=80=9D The organizatio=
n is expanding beyond its blogging roots to become a non-profit research or=
ganization and career accelerator for public intellectuals in progress stud=
ies. If you like what you=E2=80=99re reading in the Weekly Dose of Optimism=
, this is a chance to go study and do the kind of work that we talk about h=
ere!=20
Double Bonus: The Metaverse: And How It Will Revolutionize Everything [http=
s://substack.com/redirect/12a84078-3bc2-469b-bfe3-01456a8f7761?u=3D16283549=
]
Matthew Ball [https://substack.com/redirect/36fd5dcf-a736-4b72-aac3-3c164c9=
6df0c?u=3D16283549] is my favorite Metaverse writer, and his new book is th=
e deepest dive yet into the what, how, why, and when of the Metaverse. Earl=
y in the book, Ball writes =E2=80=9CThe Program is More Optimistic Than the=
 Pen=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 while the Metaverse typically appears in novels as =
a dystopia, the reality will likely be that we spend time in the Metaverse =
not to escape a hellish meatspace, but to replace TV and 2D screen time wit=
h something more useful, richer, more connective, and more fun.=20
